President Obama has proclaimed March 1-7, 2015 as National Consumer Protection Week. The proclamation emphasizes the need to protect Americans from financial fraud and identity theft and ensure that the economy provides opportunities for everyone to succeed. The administration aims to create a national standard for stolen or misused information and is encouraging companies to provide consumers with free access to their credit scores. The President also calls on Congress to pass cybersecurity legislation and proposes a rule to require retirement advisors to prioritize clients' financial interests. The Federal Government is transitioning to a more secure chip and PIN payment system as part of the BuySecure Initiative. The President encourages individuals to educate themselves about their rights and the available resources to protect against scams and fraud. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of safeguarding consumers and growing the economy while preserving privacy rights.